# Nginx upload size (fixes 413 Request Entity Too Large)

The HTML `413` page from nginx means the reverse proxy rejected the request **before** it reached Next.js.
Increase the body limit on the server that runs nginx (e.g. AWS EC2, VPS).

## Quick fix

Edit your nginx site config (often `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` or `/etc/nginx/sites-available/store1920`):

```nginx
http {
    # Allow large product/media uploads (default is often 1m)
    client_max_body_size 200M;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name your-domain.com;

    client_max_body_size 200M;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;

        # Timeouts for slow uploads
        proxy_read_timeout 300s;
        proxy_send_timeout 300s;
    }
}
```

Then reload nginx:

```bash
sudo nginx -t && sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

## App-side mitigations (already in codebase)

1. **Client compression** — images are resized/compressed before upload (`lib/compressImageForUpload.js`).
2. **Direct S3 upload** — `/api/store/upload/presign` returns a presigned URL so files go **browser → S3**, bypassing nginx.
3. **Server optimization** — `sharp` compresses images on API routes before storing.

Product save now uploads media to S3 first, then sends only URLs in the form (small JSON payload).

## S3 CORS (required for direct browser upload)

In the S3 bucket CORS configuration, allow PUT from your storefront domain:

```json
[
  {
    "AllowedHeaders": ["*"],
    "AllowedMethods": ["PUT", "GET", "HEAD"],
    "AllowedOrigins": ["https://your-domain.com", "http://localhost:3000"],
    "ExposeHeaders": ["ETag"],
    "MaxAgeSeconds": 3000
  }
]
```
